snippet.textDisplay: How did you not realize the shifter is in the same placement as in a GT40, but on the other side of the car, since it's left-hand drive?!?! lol  Not to mention all of the other GM parts you didn't notice.  I feel like you're too young to even be reviewing this, but it was a great walkthrough, regardless.  I'm not trying to be a dick, at all, but I laughed several times at some of the things that lost you.  Also, the trunk is good for a full set of golf clubs, which back in the day, particularly on a car this expensive, is how they measured trunk space, by whether or not you could fit a set of golf clubs in it, and how many may fit.

snippet.textDisplay:
I imagine the window motors are from a power sliding rear vent window off a pick up truck. Did they have those in 1989? Or maybe a sunroof motor. If they ever fail that's where I'd look for workable spares. The fuel cap looks to be a genuine aircraft part too, I'm integrating a very similar one from a Tornado in to my MGB as a nod to my late father's flying career.

The fact that the screen is still working after all this time is incredible. Well done to the team that made that!

snippet.textDisplay:
ahhhh I'm so glad you did this car. Nowhere else would I be able to get nitty gritty details on it.
Vector really should still be around. What's amazing about this car, is also how reliable it is because deep down inside it's just a pushrod 350, and a TH350 automatic trans. Quite unbelievable that they manage to make the fastest care in the world with what is essentially backyard hotrod parts.
It's not extremely fancy and proprietary at all under the hood, but it somehow became incredibly fast for what it was. It wasn't just a one off engineering marvel, it was a genuinely viable car.
Really sucks, that it didn't go anywhere, it really should have, and it shows that sometimes business can really get in the way of progress.
This is one of my fantasy cars. So much more than any modern lambo or mclaren.

snippet.textDisplay: I met Jerry Weigert at my restaurant in the eighties.  Since I was a Ferrari collector, he thought I was a buyer and he invited me to his shop to drive the prototype.  We took the car out on the Santa Monica Freeway early in the morning and I was able to drive the car flat out.  The prototype had a ratchet type shifter built into the rocker panel.  The car was a beast.  One of my most memorable driving experiences ever.  The guy was an engineering genius.  He had also designed an aqua cycle that I was unable to try out.  Cool car.

snippet.textDisplay:
Initially this post looked quite interesting right up to the wipers. It's really just an overpriced kit car, of which there were many in the 80's and early 90's. It looks very similar to many of the kits sold at that time. A 3 speed auto on a performance car? Classic kit car. Borrowed bits from mainstream vehicles? Classic kit car. Radical, outlandish styling? Classic kit car. Oversized, overpowered engine in plastic body? Classic kit car. It's little wonder they only sold 20, only 20 people were gullible enough to buy one.
It looks like they took a Countach kit and stuck another body on it.

snippet.textDisplay:
Those air vents while indeed small are similar, if not the same, as the ones you get on passenger jets to blow all that good, recycled, germ enriched, cold air on you. I may be wrong, but I believe (at least some) fighter jets also have them.
Those seats are Recaro Classics, which came just the way you see them in the car...which explains the Classic name on the plastic bezel. I'm actually quite surprised that you (a car guy) couldn't at least tell that they were Recaros. Lovely seats.
Lastly, after waiting nearly 40mins, I'd think you'd have taken right up to the mark to at least show us a bit of driving but since you didn't I now feel cheated which is yhe reason I haven't subscribed or liked the video...how could I after editing all that time, only to be denied what you said we'd get at the beginning of the video...NOT cool!
